## Behavioral Patterns

### 1. Building at the Scale of the Person He Wants to Be, Before Earning the Right

At SKIMS: changed his title before it was granted. Post-SKIMS: built a full lo-fi radio station with contracted composer, hired animator, and brand identity before having a single viewer. The brand exercise that clarified everything came months after the money was spent.

The pattern isn't delusion. The things he builds are real and often good. He skips the ugly, small, unsexy version and goes straight to the version that matches his internal sense of who he is, because the small version feels like it doesn't represent him.

**The fix:** One question before building starts — what is the cheapest, fastest way to test whether this works before investing in making it beautiful? Build ugly first. Validate. Then make it beautiful.

### 2. Going Clinical Under Pressure

When stressed — financially, professionally, relationally — he switches from warm and relational to numbered lists and clinical efficiency. This happened at SKIMS (withdrawing, apology emails after emotional moments). It happened in the Carson negotiation (scope corrections email sent the morning after a warm collaborative exchange was essentially a handshake deal). Under financial stress, the clinical mode feels safer. By the time the warmth comes out, it's cleanup.

**The pattern:** His relational instincts are better than his strategic instincts. When his gut says apologize, he should apologize.

### 3. The Myths as Infinite Foundation

He has a tendency to stay in the safe part of the work — worldbuilding, cosmology, lore, foundation — instead of moving into the scary part, which is writing the novel and putting it in front of people who will judge it. The myths are genuinely massive in scope and the work is real. But "done" needs a boundary. Finish the six texts. Let the civilization document keep evolving. Then write Only Us.

### 4. Premature Self-Authorization

The title change at SKIMS. The resentment when recognition didn't follow. When he starts feeling "owed," his judgment narrows.

### 5. The Grip

He rarely responds to texts. His explanation: "I'm so focused on my shit. Feels like if I let go of my dreams for a second they'll fall through my hands." This is vigilance, not confidence. The dream doesn't require him to be alone. He's been telling himself it does because the aloneness came so naturally it felt like proof.

### 6. Isolation Under Pressure

When things get hard, he withdraws. He calls it professional focus. It's protection. When he goes quiet, something is probably wrong. Each small failure becomes evidence in a case he's building against himself — proof he's safer alone — when the actual evidence shows that people want him in their lives despite the mistakes. He is harder on himself than anyone in his life is on him.

