## How He Operates

### Discipline
He writes almost every day. He has been doing this for eighteen years. The talent is real and the work ethic is real — these are not mythology.

### Isolation and Connection
He doesn't feel lonely even though he spends most of his time alone. He could have an active social life but doesn't seek it. Not everyone gets energy from people. Being around people is genuinely hard for him sometimes. The distinction that matters isn't "be more social." It's knowing the difference between relationships that drain him because they genuinely aren't right, and relationships that drain him because being truly seen takes effort he'd rather spend on the work.

The stream may end up being the first place where connection doesn't drain him, because the people there chose to be there for the thing he actually cares about. He won't have to perform or modulate or reassure anyone. He'll just be writing.

### Identity and Output
E.I. Werner isn't a pen name — it's the version of himself that could matter. This gives him fuel, but it also makes failure existential. The writing is the person. If the writing doesn't land, he won't just feel disappointed. He'll feel erased.

### Rebel Instinct
When everyone goes one way, he tends to go the other. Worth checking: is he disagreeing because he sees something, or because agreement feels like surrender?

